SIMPLE: furrow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Furrow
<hw>Fur"row</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>forow</ets>,
<ets>forgh</ets>, <ets>furgh</ets>, AS. <ets>furh</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>voor</ets>, OHG. <ets>furuh</ets>, G. <ets>furche</ets>, Dan.
<ets>fure</ets>, Sw. <ets>f<?/ra</ets>, Icel. for drain, L.
<ets>porca</ets> ridge between two furrows.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
trench in the earth made by, or as by, a plow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any trench, channel, or groove, as in wood or metal;
a wrinkle on the face; <as>as, the furrows of age</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Farrow weed</b></col> <cd>a weed which grows on plowed
land.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To draw a straight
furrow</b></col>, <cd>to live correctly; not to deviate from the right
line of duty.</cd> <au>Lowell.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Furrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Furrow
<hw>Fur"row</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Furrowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Furrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Furrow</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>; cf. AS. <ets>fyrian</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut
a furrow in; to make furrows in; to plow; <as>as, to furrow the ground
or sea</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mark with channels or with wrinkles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou canst help time to <qex>furrow</qex> me with age.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair cheeks were <qex>furrowed</qex> with hot tears.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Furrowy</ent>⟦br⟧
